<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many words are on a page with double spacing?", answer: "A standard double-spaced page with 12-point Times New Roman font and 1-inch margins contains approximately 250 words. This is the most common academic formatting standard. Single-spaced pages contain roughly 500 words, and 1.5-spaced pages contain about 375 words." },
  { question: "Does font choice affect word count per page?", answer: "Yes, different fonts have different character widths. Times New Roman and Georgia are relatively compact, fitting about 250 words per double-spaced page. Arial and Verdana are wider, yielding about 200-225 words per page. Courier is a monospaced font that produces even fewer words per page at approximately 210." },
  { question: "How do margins affect word count?", answer: "Wider margins reduce the text area and therefore the word count per page. Standard 1-inch margins produce the highest word count. Increasing to 1.25-inch margins reduces words by roughly 8%, while 1.5-inch margins reduce words by about 16%. Some professors require specific margin sizes, so always follow assignment guidelines." },
  { question: "Should I count references and bibliography in my word count?", answer: "This depends on the assignment guidelines. In most academic contexts, the word count refers to the body text only, excluding the title page, abstract, references, appendices, and figure captions. Always check with your professor or the assignment rubric for specific counting rules." },
  { question: "How accurate is pages-to-words conversion?", answer: "Estimates based on formatting parameters are typically accurate within 5-10% for standard academic text. Factors that can cause variation include paragraph length, use of headings, block quotes, lists, tables, images, and the specific vocabulary used. Technical writing with longer words tends to have fewer words per page than conversational writing." }
]) %>

